2 e^{-x}\left(1-e^{-x}\right) & 0 < x < \infty \\
0 & \text { elsewhere }
\end{array}\right.
How can we sample from this distribution?

Choices:
Suppose Y  and X \mid Y have the respective pdfs
f_{Y}(y) & =\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
2 e^{-2 y} & 0 < x < \infty \\
0 & \text { elsewhere }
\end{array}\right. \\
f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid y) & =\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
e^{-(x-y)} & y < x < \infty \\
0 & \text { elsewhere }
\end{array}\right.
Suppose we generate random variables by the following algorithm:
1. Generate \( Y \sim f_{Y}(y) \)
2. Generate \( X \sim f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid Y) \)
Then,  X  has the pdf requested. Furthermore, it is easy to generate from the pdfs f_{Y}(y) and f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid y) because the inverses of the respective cdfs are given by  F_{Y}^{-1}(u)=-2^{-1} \log (1-u)  and  F_{X \mid Y}^{-1}(u)=-\log (1-u)+Y .

Suppose Y  and X \mid Y have the respective pdfs
f_{Y}(y) & =\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
 e^{- y} & 0 < x < \infty \\
0 & \text { elsewhere }
\end{array}\right. \\
f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid y) & =\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
e^{-(x-y)} & y < x < \infty \\
0 & \text { elsewhere }
\end{array}\right.
Suppose we generate random variables by the following algorithm:
1. Generate \( Y \sim f_{Y}(y) \)
2. Generate \( X \sim f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid Y) \)
Then,  X  has the pdf requested. Furthermore, it is easy to generate from the pdfs f_{Y}(y) and f_{X \mid Y}(x \mid y) because the inverses of the respective cdfs are given by  F_{Y}^{-1}(u)=- \log (1-u)  and  F_{X \mid Y}^{-1}(u)=-\log (1-u)+Y .

